<TITLE> Hamas disputes Abbas comments on truce deal terms </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 GAZA, March 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Hamas denied on Tuesday comments by its rival, Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas, that its pursuit of an Egyptian-mediated truce with Israel was motivated by a desire to protect its leaders from Israeli assassination. "These remarks are nothing but lies aimed at damaging Hamas's image," Sami Abu Zuhri, an official of the Islamist group said in a statement, issued amid a lull in violence between Israel and militants in the Hamas-run Gaza Strip. "Hamas leaders seek martyrdom and would never bargain over the blood of their people like others do," Abu Zuhri said. Abbas said in Amman on Monday that Hamas and Islamic Jihad, the main groups in the Gaza Strip behind cross-border rocket fire at Israel, wanted assurances that in return for agreeing to a truce, their leaders would not be attacked. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert has threatened to target all those behind the rocket strikes, raising speculation that Hamas's political leadership could be on the firing line. Israel assassinated top Hamas leaders Ahmed Yassin and Abdel Aziz al-Rantissi in the Gaza Strip in 2004. Hamas, which seized control of the Gaza Strip from Abbas's Fatah faction in fighting last June, has been holding its fire against Israel for the past seven days. Islamic Jihad last carried out a rocket attack on Wednesday. Israel also has ceased its air and ground operations in the Gaza Strip since ending last Monday a five-day offensive that killed 120 Palestinians, about half of whom have been identified as civilians. A Gaza truce could be key to US-brokered peace efforts between Israel and Abbas. Amid much scepticism, Washington hopes the negotiations can lead to a Palestinian statehood deal by the end of the year. Abbas's chief negotiator, Ahmed Qurie, said in the West Bank city of Ramallah that Israel's announcement on Sunday that it would build hundreds of new homes in Givat Ze'ev, a Jewish settlement in the West Bank, was a "blow to the peace process". Bu